==External links== * [http://www.encyclopediaofmath.org/index.php/Meta-theorem ''Meta-theorem'' at Encyclopaedia of Mathematics] * {{MathWorld|urlname=Metatheorem|title=Metatheorem|author=Barile, Margherita}}
{{Metalogic}}
[[Category:Metalogic]] [[Category:Mathematical terminology]] [[Category:Metatheorems| ]]

In mathematics, '''Mumford's compactness theorem''' states that the space of [[compact space|compact]] [[Riemann surface]]s of fixed [[genus (mathematics)|genus]] ''g''&nbsp;>&nbsp;1 with no [[closed geodesic]]s of length less than some fixed ''&epsilon;''&nbsp;>&nbsp;0 in the [[Poincaré metric]] is compact. It was proved by {{harvs|txt|first=David|last=Mumford|authorlink=David Mumford|year=1971}} as a consequence of a theorem about the compactness of sets of discrete subgroups of [[semisimple Lie group]]s generalizing [[Mahler's compactness theorem]].
==References== *{{citation|last=Mumford|first=David|year=1971|jstor=2037802|title=A remark on Mahler's compactness theorem|journal=Proceedings of the American Mathematical Society|volume=28|pages=289–294|mr=0276410|doi=10.2307/2037802|url=https://dash.harvard.edu/bitstream/handle/1/3612773/Mumford_RemarkMahlerComp.pdf?sequence=3}}
[[Category:Riemann surfaces]] [[Category:Kleinian groups]] [[Category:Compactness theorems]]
{{mathematics-stub}}

{{Lie groups |Homogeneous spaces}}
In [[mathematics]], '''restricted root systems''', sometimes called '''relative root systems''', are the [[root system]]s associated with a [[symmetric space]]. The associated finite reflection group is called the '''restricted Weyl group'''. The restricted root system of a symmetric space and its dual can be identified. For symmetric spaces of noncompact type arising as homogeneous spaces of a semisimple Lie group, the restricted root system and its Weyl group are related to the [[Iwasawa decomposition]] of the Lie group.

